title: Approaching monster hurricane cancels Sea-Tac-Puerto Vallarta...
text:
Flights to Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, from Sea-Tac Airport are being canceled as a hurricane is expect to make landfall south of there Friday night.
Alaska Airlines canceled its only flight to the city Friday morning.
Hurricane Patricia is a category 5 storm with winds in excess of 200 mph and is the strongest ever in the Western Hemisphere.
Forecasters say it could make a "potentially catastrophic landfall.”
Latest stories, maps of Hurricane Patricia PHOTOS: History's most destructive hurricanes A satellite image Friday morning showed bands of rain from the hurricane extending thousands of miles from the eye.
The storm is forecast to slam into Southwest Mexico Friday evening with high winds and up to a foot of rain.
"It seems incredible that even more strengthening could occur before landfall later today,"- @NHC_Pacific #Patricia https://t.co/AUEnuiYaJb ?
— Morgan Palmer (@MorganKIRO7) October 23, 2015 KIRO 7 meteorologist Todd Johnson said there has been only one time in recorded history that a category 5 storm has slammed into the Pacific coast of Mexico.
Patricia's power was comparable to that of Typhoon Haiyan, which left more than 7,300 dead or missing in the Philippines two years ago, according to the U.N.'s World Meteorological Organization.
More than 4 million people were displaced and more than 1 million houses were destroyed or damaged.
